Two things I saw that did get my attention but wasn't immediately clear what the decision was:

1. Regarding event handler attributes:
> I originally proposed that we do the same thing as preact here (forward everything starting with "on" to addEventListener), but if I remember correctly Sebastian felt strongly that we shouldn't reserve everything starting with "on" for event listeners. Jason Miller also felt strongly about this the other way, so maybe it's something that I can revisit/discuss more after merging this PR - maybe more users will chime in if they get to test it out.

Is this an argument React should even be having? [The standard](https://html.spec.whatwg.org/dev/webappapis.html#event-handler-attributes) says: "the event handler [content attribute or IDL] is exposed through a name, which is a string that always starts with "on" and is followed by the name of the event for which the handler is intended." 
There are no non-event HTML attributes that start with "on" for this reason. Web Component authors must follow this, including custom attributes and custom events, so React simply needs to follow the spec here.

2. In the linked Google doc this doesn't sound like the right design:
>we avoid showing the custom element until it is defined

The Custom Element definition may never come (e.g. web server is down, network is slow/stalled, developer failed to include script), but browsers today can and do immediately render yet-to-be-defined custom elements in the DOM because they're designed to be fast and fault tolerant. 

Not only that, but Custom Element authors don't always want/need to use shadow DOM, so browsers can and do immediately begin to style custom elements with global styles. Again, the CE definition may still be on its way or a multitude of errors prevent it from ever downloading/evaluating, but that's not a reason to halt rendering what can be rendered. 

Lastly, and I'm biased here, but I personally use all of this to my advantage ([TAC CSS methodology](https://jordanbrennan.hashnode.dev/tac-a-new-css-methodology), [Mdash](http://m-docs.org)). 
For example, basic custom elements like an icon or badge have no need for JavaScript, so I don't create CE definitions for them. But the API of custom elements (i.e. tag and attributes) is better than a bunch of goofy classes, so this is what I do: 

Icon component with custom HTML tag, it's 100% vanilla CSS, and no CE definition
```
/* Icon base styles */
m-icon {
  display: inline-flex;

  &::before {
    font-family: 'm-icons'; /* Mdash uses Material Symbols Outlined with filled option */
    content: attr(name);
    -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
  }

  /* Filled option */
  &[fill]::before { font-variation-settings: 'FILL' 1 }
}
```
And developers use it just like HTML because it is HTML:
```
<p>Material Symbols star icon <m-icon name="star"></m-icon></p>
<p>Material Symbols filled star icon <m-icon name="star" fill></m-icon></p>
```
Works literally everywhere. Been doing it for 5+ years now in dozens of projects - static HTML, SSR, CSR, with frameworks including React and without - and it's been great. Sometimes these CSS-only elements get new requirements that have to use JavaScript and then I add a CE definition for that behavior, but the markup and styles do not change. It's like progressive enhancement for Custom Elements.

So, please do not break this by waiting for CE to be defined in order to render! Custom HTML like this has been possible for decades and is supported by all browsers for almost just as long. React should follow the browser and every other framework and render what is given to it. Let the CE definition do whatever it does _if and when it exists_.
